                    <head>Breviary (fragmented)</head>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <p>
                                        <locusGrp>
                                            <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                            <locus from="L1" to="L3" scheme="folios"/>
                                            <locus from="217" to="217" scheme="folios"/>
                                            <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                        </locusGrp>
                                        <note>See Collation for more information on the structure of the support in relation to the text block.</note>
                                        <material>Parchment</material>
                                        <dimensions type="leaf">
                                            <height quantity="160" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="105" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </p>
                                </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure type="leftFlyleaves" quantity="3" unit="folios"/>
                                    <measure type="rightFlyleaves" quantity="1" unit="folios"/>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil. Error in foliation: f. I-III, 1-96, 98-106, 106a, 107-182, 182bis, 183-217. <secFol>prompte eum in tenebras</secFol>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <formula>1(4), 2-5(10), 6(12), 7(10), 8-10(12), 11(1+8), 12(10, lacks 10), 13(10, lacks 1), 14-20(10), 21(12), 22(10+2). </formula>
                                    <p>
                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/69f87dd06e6f4a0001f9b362/viewOnly">VisColl collation</ref>. The first and parts of the last quire properly belongs to the binding. The first quire consist of two parchment bifolia, the first of which is part of the pastedown (<locus from="LCI" to="L3" scheme="other"/>). The last quire also contain two parchment bifolia, but mixed with 4 paper bifolia. The first parchment bifolium (<locus from="207" to="207" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="216" to="216" scheme="folios"/>) envelopes the paper quire on <locus from="208" to="215" scheme="folios"/>, and the second bifolium makes up the last leaf of the manuscript and the pastedown (<locus from="217" to="217" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="folios"/>). Since all of these leaves contain text they are included in the collation formula. Parchment guards at the centre of each quire.</p>
                                    <signatures>Quire signatures in Arabic numerals by a medieval hand. Signatures partially trimmed, first visible on <locus from="11r" to="11r" scheme="folios"/>, last on <locus from="176r" to="176r" scheme="folios"/>.</signatures>
                                </collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner: National Library book label; centre page, in ink by a modern hand: <quote>103 970</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Brown leather over bevelled wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. Originally, two clasps with Y-shaped catchplates. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, in ink: <quote>Breviarium.</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 186</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="160" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="110" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="45" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Complex blind tooling consisiting of panels filled with different stamped geometrical shapes as well as flowers and vinestems.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather worn. <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>, several holes in the cover. Clasps and catchplates missing.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName cert="low" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                </origPlace>,<origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1480"> 15th century, last quarter</origDate>. The inclusion of texts in German, e.g on <locus from="206r" to="206r" scheme="folios"/>, indicates the German speaking lands as place of origin. On <locus from="L2v" to="L2v" scheme="folios"/> the date <date when="1489"/> is mentioned; on <locus from="98r" to="98r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <date when="1482"/>, and on <locus from="205vb" to="205vb" scheme="folios"/> a rubric mentions a date, but the numbers have been partially erased, it reads: <quote>finit anno domini 148-</quote>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Provenance unknown.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National LIbrary</orgName> from the book dealer <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100192">Björk och Börjesson</orgName> in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100078">Stockholm</placeName>, July 1, <date when="1917"/> for 200 kronor.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
                    <msPart>
                        <msIdentifier>
                            <idno type="codicologicalUnit">1</idno>
                        </msIdentifier>
                        <msContents>
                            <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="L1r" to="L3v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Miscellanous texts</title>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="L1r" to="L1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Blessing of the wine</title>
                                    <rubric>Inicium sancti enay? Benediccio vini sancti iohannis </rubric>
                                    <incipit>secundum iohannem In principio erat verbum et cetera (Ioh. 1:1) per totum Domine ihesu christe qui es vitis vera</incipit>
                                    <explicit>per christum dominum meum amen</explicit>
                                    <note>
                                        <locus from="L1v" to="L1v" scheme="folios"/>: on the verso are several medical recipes written by a different medieval hand. See also the additions on <locus from="L2v" to="L2v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="206" to="206" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="217v" to="217v" scheme="folios"/>.</note>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="L2r" to="L2v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Formula for absolution</title>
                                    <rubric>Forma absolucionis anni iubilei religiosorum </rubric>
                                    <incipit>Dominus inc? ihesus christus per suam piissimam misericordiam </incipit>
                                    <explicit>e a dicto domino meo nicolao quinto congressam pro ultimo articulo/arbitrio/argumento mortis tue In nomine patris et filii et spiritus sancti Amen</explicit>
                                    <note>The text refers to Nicholas V, which would indicate the Jubilee of 1450. After the main text follows three paragraphs by different medieval hands, the first in German, the second and third in what seems to be a mixture of Latin and German. The last two may be medical recipes.</note>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="L3r" to="L3v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Notes on readings for Sundays</title>
                                    <incipit>Nota quod quandocumque aliqua hystoria sit expleta in dominica</incipit>
                                    <explicit>SI hec notabis recte numquam errabis</explicit>
                                </msItem>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="1ra" to="98rb" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Proper of time</title>
                                <rubric>Incipit nocturnale simplex </rubric>
                                <incipit>Dominica prima in aduentu Invitatorium Regem venturum dominum</incipit>
                                <explicit>Isti edificabunt et ego destruam (Mal. 1:4) Tu autem domine</explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit anno domini 1482 In cathedra petri deo gracias placeat tibi? sancta trinitas</finalRubric>
                                <note>
                                    <p> Begins with the First Sunday in Advent, ends with the fourth Sunday in November.</p>
                                    <p/>
                                    <p/>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="98va" to="102vb" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Supplementary readings</title>
                                <rubric>Supplementum ob- de epistulos</rubric>
                                <incipit>SAulus serus ihesu kristi vocatus apostolus (Rom. 1:1)</incipit>
                                <explicit>Qui autem facit voluntatem dei manet in eternum (1 Ioh. 2:17)</explicit>
                                <note>
                                    <p>Additional readings for Sundays, especially the Easter week and the weeks after Easter.</p>
                                    <p/>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="103r" to="107r" scheme="folios"/>: ruled, but not text.</p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="107va" to="205vb" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Proper of saints</title>
                                <incipit defective="true">? ihesu christi apostolo Cuius passionem quam coram positi vidimus</incipit>
                                <explicit>laus et gloria in secula/-orum amen Tu autem domine et cetera</explicit>
                                <finalRubric>finit anno domini 148<unclear quantity="1" unit="chars"/>
                                </finalRubric>
                                <note>
                                    <p> Fragmented, begins in the middle of St Andrew (30 Nov). Then follows what seem to be shorter offices for St Saturnine (29 Nov.), St Andrew again, St Nicholas (6 Dec.) and so on, ending wihth St Catherine (25 Nov.).</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="206" to="206" scheme="folios"/> previously a ruled but blank leaf has been filled with medical recipes written by a medieval hand in a mix of Latin and German.</p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="207r" to="215rb" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Common of saints</title>
                                <incipit defective="true">Eterna christi munera apostolorum gloria laudes canentes</incipit>
                                <explicit>alterum se non invitatus invitat</explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit</finalRubric>
                                <note>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="207r" to="207r" scheme="folios"/>: this sections begins in the middle of the Common of apostles;</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="208rb" to="208rb" scheme="folios"/>: Common of evangelists;</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="209ra" to="209ra" scheme="folios"/>: Common of one martyr;</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="209vb" to="209vb" scheme="folios"/>: Common of many martyrs;</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="210vb" to="210vb" scheme="folios"/>: Common of one confessor;</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="212vb" to="212vb" scheme="folios"/>: Common of many virgins (with exceptions for different kinds of female saints on <locus from="213vb" to="214ra" scheme="folios"/>);</p>
                                    <p/>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="214ra" to="214ra" scheme="folios"/>: in dedicatione templi;</p>
                                    <p> On <locus from="207" to="207" scheme="folios"/> the text is written in one column on parchment, <locus from="208" to="215" scheme="folios"/> in two columns on paper.</p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="215va" to="217v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Office and instructions for the visitation of the sick</title>
                                <rubric>Ordo minorum fratrum secundum consuetudinem romane ecclesie ad visitandum infirmum</rubric>
                                <incipit>In primis pulsetur campana parua et fratres qui possunt in ecclesia conveniant</incipit>
                                <explicit>tu venia misericordissme pietatis absterge per christum dominum</explicit>
                                <note>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="215" to="216" scheme="folios"/>: the text is written in two columns on paper, but on <locus from="217" to="217" scheme="folios"/> in one column on parchment.</p>
                                    <p> After the main text follows a short addition by another medieval hand consisting of a recipe written in a mixture of German and Latin.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>: a leaf with text from the Proper of time, Palm Sunday with mention of a station church (the Lateran).</p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msContents>
                        <physDesc>
                            <objectDesc>
                                <supportDesc material="paper">
                                    <support>
                                        <p>
                                            <locus from="1" to="216" scheme="folios"/>
                                            <material>Western paper</material>
                                            <dimensions type="leaf">
                                                <height quantity="155" unit="mm"/>
                                                <width quantity="105" unit="mm"/>
                                            </dimensions>
                                            <note>In the first part of the manuscript there are two different types of oxheads visible at the top of the leaves. The motives are not completely visible but seem to consist of a a oxhead with eyes and ears; above, single or double line rod ending in flower. From <locus from="105" to="105" scheme="folios"/> the watermark changes to a crown with 5 points; above a double line rod ending in flower with 7 petals.</note>
                                        </p>
                                    </support>
                                    <extent>
                                        <measure type="textblockLeaves" quantity="217" unit="folios"/>
                                    </extent>
                                    <condition>Paper stained in places. Damage from silverfish or bookwork in places, most visible close to the gutter, especially towards the end, e.g. on <locus from="201" to="202" scheme="folios"/>.</condition>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout columns="2" ruledLines="30">
                                        <dimensions type="written">
                                            <height quantity="110" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="75" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                        <note>Ruling and guidelines in ink. Pricking in margins. There are a few leaves that does not follow the layout above, e.g. with text in one column.</note>
                                    </layout>
                                </layoutDesc>
                            </objectDesc>
                            <handDesc>
                                <p>The identification of hands is tentative. There are several but fairly similar hands discernible, further hands may be possible to identify. Besides the hands identified below there are additions by several hands on <locus from="L1" to="L3" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="217v" to="217v" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-1">
                                    <locusGrp>
                                        <locus from="1ra" to="98rb" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="107va" to="205vb" scheme="folios"/>
                                    </locusGrp>Hybrida (perhaps more than one hand). </handNote>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-2">
                                    <locus from="98va" to="102vb" scheme="folios"/>Hybrida.</handNote>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-3">
                                    <locus from="207r" to="215rb" scheme="folios"/>Hybrida.</handNote>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-4">
                                    <locus from="215va" to="217v" scheme="folios"/>Hybrida. </handNote>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="217v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Scattered additions in the margins by one or several contemporary hands. The additions usually consist of corrections or missing text supplied with signe-de-renvoi, e.g. on <locus from="5r" to="5r" scheme="folios"/>. There are also several manicules, e.g. on <locus from="27v" to="27v" scheme="folios"/> or <locus from="132r" to="132r" scheme="folios"/>. There are several longer additions by different hands after the mains texts, see Contents.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="9v" to="9v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Pen drawing of the Christ child in the stable lying next to two animals, with Joseph(?) sitting on a chair. Drawn in ink with details in red and a splash of green.</note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in brown ink, rubrics in red, capitals touched in red.</p>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="1ra" to="216vb" scheme="folios"/>: plain initials over 1-2 lines in red.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
                        </physDesc>
                    </msPart>
                </msDesc>
            </sourceDesc>
